segments.text: What were, as the wife of the land commissioner, what were your social responsibilities in Austin?
Well, all the state official ladies had to belong to state official ladies club, so I was a member of that.
And even after I came here, Earl insisted I keep my membership.
I did for a ton of years.
So I went to that.
Who were your favorite state official ladies during those years?
Well, Rue Walker's wife, he was on the court, Supreme Court, Virginia.
I don't know, Mary Alice Shivers.
You know, she just died a couple years ago.
And she and I had a good mutual friend.
And as soon as I heard that she had died, I called Anna Mae Morrison.
Now, her husband was not a state official,
But Shivers went into business with Anna Mae's husband after he left the governor's office.
Anyway, I called her, and she said that she had talked to her just a couple of days before she died.
And she said, Anna Mae, I don't want anybody standing up looking at me in the casket.
Said, if you have to, just sit on that lid to keep it from opening.
OK, that's all.
All right, so.
Oh, Weldon Hart was Shiver's right-hand man, and his wife was a good friend.
I don't know.
All right, you all are there.
The kids are in school.
In four different schools part of the time.
And you've got a comfortable house.
Yeah.
How was it, who was it that communicated with Mr. Rutter about possibly coming over to College Station?
whoever was chairman of the board, but I don't think it was Pat Zachary, but Pat Zachary talked to me about it.
Like I said, Earl was real undecided if he wanted to do it because he was afraid he'd be resented.
Because he just had a lowly bachelor degree.
He'd done little work on a master's, but not a whole lot.
While we were at Tarleton, we'd drive up to Fort Worth and do it through TCU.
But Pat Zachary did, he
Talk to me, I'll never forget it.
He was the kindest person.
And he wanted me to kinda influence Earl on coming here.
Were there others that you know of that worked hard to persuade him?
Who, Earl?
Yes, ma'am.
I don't know.
But I know this, when we first came over here on the campus, and I was seeing the house we were to live in,
I thought, good heavens, I don't have enough furniture to furnish that big old house.
And you know what happened to it.
We'd been in it five years.
We'll get to that in a minute.
All right, so you all moved over here when?
We moved over here the 20...
I think it was around the 26th of January of 1958, the start of the second semester.
That's what I had thought.
And you moved into that big house.
Was there some furniture already there?
Oh, yeah.
The university had furnished almost all of the downstairs.
Now, we had to buy breakfast room furniture, but
All the downstairs furniture was university, and a lot of it is in use still in the President's House on campus.
Right.
Did you keep all of your furniture from the Austin house?
Or did you get rid of some?
Oh, yeah, but it didn't amount to a whole lot.
Okay.
It was upstairs, so it got burned.
And this house was west of Sabeasa.
You know, I've never been in those directions, but it was first lived in by Lawrence Sullivan Ross.
That was a point to remember.
Right.
1892, I think, it was built.
How did you feel that you were received by the local community?
They were always nice, but I was, oh, heavens, I was afraid.
Like I said, nobody told me what I was supposed to do.
And you didn't know, you didn't have any...
I didn't have any background for it.
And you didn't have any friend here in advance, did you?
You didn't know any of the wives or...
Now, the Davises had had us over for a military weekend while Earl was still in the land office.
I'll never forget that.
I met Lupo.
We got out there, and actually, we had left Brady, and they wanted me to bring Bud with me.
What's your time doing?
I'm doing fine.
Bring Bud because the Davises had Steadman.
Did you know he had died several years ago?
No.
And see, Bud is now 58, and Stedman was probably the same age.
And he died.
I don't know what reason or anything.
Don't know what about Joe or...
I kind of think Marie's not living, but anyway.
We came down, and it was just this balmy weather.
Flowers were blooming in Austin.
We picked Earl up in Austin.
And...
You know, see, what happened to Earl?
He didn't have time to look for a place, and he was staying in the Commodore Perry Hotel.
I don't know whether it's even there now or not.
But Jake Pickle heard that Earl was staying there.
And see, Jake's first wife had died.
And they had just the one little girl, Peggy.
And so his wife's parents took Peggy.
And so Jake could still work.
And anyway...

he when he heard that Earl was staying at the hotel and he was out there in the house by himself so he just go down and said Earl this is silly he said just pack your stuff and come on out and stay at my house with me so Earl did and he stayed there from January till we got moved in August anyway what was your first reaction to College Station
Amazement, I guess.
I don't know.
I was still trying to find out what I was supposed to do.
But, you know, it goes on years and years.
Who was it left?
Gordon Eaton, was that a name?
He went to University of Iowa, maybe?
Iowa State.
Iowa State, yeah.
And she came to me.
She said, somebody told me that I should talk to you about...
what I should do is being a university president.
I said, the only thing I can tell you is just be yourself.
That's all I could, I didn't have any magic words at all.
As far as you know, when you all came here, was Mr. Rutter given any directions by the board or anybody as to what he was to do?
He was to be in charge of this campus.
Was he supposed to straighten anything out or clean anything up?
You know, I don't really remember that.
I don't know.
I really don't know.
But I know that Earl, from the time we got here, he would always call Mr. Heaton to find out what the enrollment was as soon as they registered.
And he was keeping his eye on that enrollment because it wasn't going anywhere.
That's right.
It was just stagnant.
And so
He knew that some changes had to be made.
I don't know how Earl knew these things.
I tell you what, I finally decided years and years later that I felt like he went through so much in World War II.
And if he could live through that, he could do about anything.
Sure.
But the changes that were made, the most controversial, of course, was letting the girls in.
And, of course, he had help on that board and everything.
As of late, it looked like somebody else made all those decisions, you know, but anyway, he was pretty involved.
And when he got up and announced to the student body, all male, all military, that the girls would be coming, they booed him.
And that was the most controversial.
The next most controversial was allowing the Corps to be optional.
But there were old Aggies that didn't speak to him again after that.
Oh, you know one in Beaumont.
Yes, that's Charlie Babcock.
As you all got started here,
How did the children react?
Well, it's funny.
I was most concerned about Ann.
See, Bud was already in A&M, but Ann had the nicest bunch of friends in Austin that you'd ever want your daughter to have, and I was worried about how she'd feel.
Well, at the end of that first year, I told Earl, much to his amazement, that when he went to summer camp, I was going to take the kids and go over, and we still hadn't sold our house in Austin.
I was going to

take the kids over there and we were going to stay there and we had a wonderful time didn't have any furniture we took sleeping bags and Jane had a slumber party for her birthday because it was always when Earl was gone they just had a great time and Earl said you can't stay in the house that had any furniture I said that's all right we'll just take sleeping bags and we drove into Austin and Ann's remark was I wouldn't move back here for a million dollars

she had just fit right in from the time we came here because in my interview with her i got that impression did you interview her yes ma'am about two weeks ago yeah and let's see now one of the questions i asked her i'd like to compare your answer i said and based on your recollections what

big worries frustrations problems do you remember your dad talking about he didn't talk at the house from the office and she said he never broke no he didn't and that's why i was just so dumb i didn't i didn't know what was going on somebody tell me something i'd tell earl he said i knew that long ago
Now, I assumed that part of that came from his military experience.
Could have been.
That maybe you don't take the battle plans and discuss them.
He just never brought any university business home.
Now, when y'all first got here, where was his office located?
In the Koch Building.
All right, so even from the first, in the Koch Building.
Yeah.
All right.
Now, his title at first was executive vice president?
Just vice president, I think.
Okay.
And then he became president.
But he was in charge of this campus.
Yes, ma'am.
And then the next year, in 59, he was named president.
And, of course, in 65...
He was named head of the system.
Both.
I remember that.
President of the university and of the system.
In those earliest years, on whom do you think he most relied?
Who were his?
I'm finding out.
Wayne Hall and Dorsey McCrory.
See, Dorsey was his first assistant.
Right.
Now, where did he first know Dorsey?
I don't know.
He never told me that.
I don't know whether they knew each other.
I kind of think there was Army Reserve connections.
Well, he had a military career, of course, Dorsey did.
But I don't know that they knew each other.
I just don't know.
And, of course, Dorothy, Dorothy McCrory's dad was Dorsey's general.
Oh, I didn't know that.
She was the general's daughter.
What parts of the task do you think Mr.
Rudder most enjoyed?
and least enjoyed of being president?
I hate to say what he would have enjoyed.
I don't know.
He just enjoyed always working with young people, young men particularly.
And I don't know what he least enjoyed.
I don't know.
He never told me.
He never said, I don't enjoy this.
Like, I don't think he enjoyed making speeches.
Oh, no, he didn't.
You're right there.

he didn't on the other hand I have the impression that he did enjoy going to Austin and Washington into the real world of politics because he knew so many people you know when Ed Cooper became his assistant and I guess that he followed Dorsey and I don't remember what Dorsey did after he was a development director that's right
But I had seen a picture of Ed in the battalion, I guess, and said he was going to be Earl's new assistant.
Earl didn't tell me that he was having him over at his luncheon before the ball game.
Of course, those luncheons were so small, they were in the assembly room, and it would only hold a certain number.
Anyway, I looked across, and there was Ed Cooper.
I knew it was him because I'd seen his picture in the paper.
happened to have caught my eye at the same time.
Well, here he came and he said, is there anything I can do for you, Miss Rutter?
I said, nobody ever asked me that before.
I was looking after Earl.
I said, I accused the battalion of photographers the same thing.
They'd get Earl looking just real pretty and I'd look like the Dickinson.
They'd snap the picture.
Let's see, Hall and McCrory.
On the board, who were the people that you remember

that mr rudder worked with most closely i don't know what i think that most closely or not but we both knew and thought the world of pat zachary and you know earl could call on him if somebody that was supposed to have made a commencement address had to cancel out at the last minute well you could ask pat zachary he could say more in fewer words than anybody i ever knew and
He was just the nicest person.
Of course, Sterling Evans was a good friend.
Earl could not have asked for a better board to work with.
I've always, in my remarks about those times of change, I've said how blessed we were at that point.
Oh, absolutely.
These were people who had made big decisions, and they were not out to try to...
make their egos bigger.
No.
They did it for the good of A&M.
That's right.
That's right.
Boyle.
Who?
Mr. Boyle from Dow Chemical.
Dr. Boyle, yeah.
He was a fine person.
Al Davies.
Al's not good right now.
Oh, really?
No.
Mildred called me.
And Dick Goodson from Southwestern Bell.
All of those people were good and positive.
Oh, absolutely good.
All right.
non-compulsory core and co-education and name change and so forth, I was on the aspirations committee and it was my job to write the draft of that report.
Was that the blueprint for progress or not?
No, that one comes later.
Okay.
And I turned it in to Vice President Hall.
He called me three or four days later
and gave me a copy which Mr. Rutter had read, a rough draft, and he had many comments and so forth.
Earl, did he?
Yes, ma'am.
Make his case.
Yes, ma'am.
Some of which were disagreement with our, and Dr. Hall had said, here, take it, redraft it.
I go back to him and I said, sir, I can't in good faith make some of these changes because our committee, these are our recommendations.
We may be in error.
But we do believe that if we don't have co-education, if we don't make the Corps volunteer, that we're not going to grow.
And the fourth change was admitting the minorities.
Right.
And that was done very smoothly.
Right.
And he said, I'll stake my job.
Who, Earl said that?
No, Hall.
See, I hadn't talked to Mr. Rutter at all.
He said, I'll stake my job on your...
opportunity to say what the committee believes.
Now, I can't guarantee you what's going to be the result, but do.
And as I have heard through the grapevine that Fred Benson and Hall both spoke up and that Mr. Rutter listened to them.
But let's try to name the others who deserve credit.

we had at that point we had Bill Moore supportive we had Sterling Evans on the board we had Buck Wirus with the association John Lindsay was the chairman or the president of the association that year and they endorsed it so we had a number are there some other people that you can think of that deserve credit I don't think so

Now, as I have heard, this is hearsay, on racial integration, the way Mr. Rutter really made it come about, that he called Washington and told the Defense Department when they sent this year's group of enlisted men at Army expense to come down here and finish their degree,
that include in this year's group some minority students.
I never heard that.
Well, as I understood it, and that then I understood that he called Mr. Heaton in and said, okay, Lloyd, you review all of their transcripts.
They've assured me that they won't send anybody whose grades are in doubt and who's in trouble or anything.
You check them out, be sure they're all, and then you call every instructor

every teacher who's going to have one of these in class and tell them that these students have been admitted, everything is in order, and I had heard myself Mr. Heaton say a year or two earlier, over my dead body will we ever have black students here.
You know, all I can remember Earl saying, I think I remember him saying this,
that instead of having them out in the line to register, which he had them come inside and registered them, they weren't ever out in the line, and then they just appeared in their classes.
And I don't remember a single mumble.
I don't either.
A single anything.
And there again.
Pretty smooth.
And it worked well, and it began in the summer.
So that then when the fall semester began, nobody could say it wouldn't work.
It had worked smoothly as could be.
Do you remember any individuals coming up to either of you to complain or to cheer about any of these changes?
I remember.
You mentioned Charlie Babcock.
We ran into him in an airport one time, and he just turned his head.
Really?
He didn't speak.
But as far as minorities, I don't know of anything, really.
I never heard any.
The only thing was when Dick Bernard was Earl's assistant.
That was down the line sometimes.
I remember him.
There was a group of them, black students, that

came in Earl was in the hospital with his blood pressure and Dick wanted he came from the office over to me said he just needed to go down tell her what had happened I said oh Dick I said he's down there with high blood pressure let's don't let's don't bother him but he went anyway well Earl couldn't get out of there fast enough they were going to come back the next day and did
But Earl just talked to them, said, is there anything that's keeping you from getting your education here?
They couldn't think of a thing that was keeping them from it.
So he said, well, just go back and hit your books.
What were they complaining about?
Don't know.
But they were marching on the office.
And they whipped out these ID cards so fast that Dick didn't know what was going on.
I don't know what's become of him.
I haven't heard of him in a long time.
He got his PhD at University of Houston, I understand.
Right.
I interviewed Ed Cooper not long ago, up at his place at the lake, and he's enjoying life.
Oh yeah.
Now let's see, and he told me that, maybe I mentioned this to you a while ago, he told me that he thought LBJ was also a positive factor
in encouraging co-education and non-compulsory core.
I didn't know he had an opinion even.
He could have had, but I don't know.
He said he thought that on one of the occasions when Mr. Rutter went to Washington to try to find some more federal money, that he said, because I realized after he came back from that trip,
he was more positive about, let's go ahead and do it.
Yeah.
And he said... Could have been.
I don't know.
And I think I can imagine Lyndon Johnson putting his arm around somebody's shoulder and giving them...
He was pretty good at encouraging.
That's what I've heard.
That's what I've heard.
Yeah.
Let's see.
Do you remember any anecdotes of Rutter and Teague or Rutter and Lupo, those classmates?
Of course, Earl and...
And Tiger were close buddies.
That's what I understood.
Oh, yeah, definitely.
He got a little disturbed about Lupo.
Oh, really?
Oh, you know, he had a hand in when they stole the mascots and all that kind of thing.
Oh, that's right.
Oh, he liked him.
But, you know, I have a picture taken at the time Earl was inaugurated
of all the ones of his class that were here for the inauguration.
And I honestly don't know how many are left now.
This Arthur Sherlock is still living.
At least I haven't heard he died.
But most of them are gone.
And I told Bubba Lupo, Lupo's son, that
I had a picture if he wanted to get a copy of it.
Now, let's see, Class of 32.
Maggie McGee was Class 31.
Maggie was a good friend.
Oh, yes, yes.
And you know, a lot of people didn't understand when they named the administration building for Connolly.
Well, he did more for higher education when he was governor than almost anybody.
Maggie provided the plane, and they had all different heads of different schools would fly all over the place for stuff.
I don't know.
I didn't understand it.
Earl didn't explain it to me.

That spring of 62, when John Connolly was running for the Democratic nomination, again, Republican nomination didn't matter then, I went out to Easterwood Airport, and he landed in a DC-3 that somebody had loaned him that had an orange rudder.

and he began his remarks by apologizing for landing on that airport with anything painted orange but he said this was loaned to me for free and if you know any Aggie that will loan me a maroon plane for free I'll use it he was a good governor did y'all visit while they were governor did y'all visit with the Connolly's son I don't remember we were close to the shivers
Okay.
But I don't know that...
So you were...
But we knew the Connellys.
Yes.
And any time that he was down here, you know, I was... Now, of your president wife days, what did you enjoy most?
What events?
What activities?
Oh, I don't know.
I enjoyed it, you know.
I'll tell you, after moving over in the current president's house, I enjoyed the flowers.
You know, they had those raised beds, and I did flower arrangements to my heart content.
I love to do that.
Let's jump back to the fire.
Okay.
That is the... 26th of January, 63.
That's what I thought.
During the old exam period, and...
It was between semesters.
That's what I mean, yeah.
And...
It happens during, begins during the daytime, doesn't it?
At noon.
And I called.
Earl was still over at the office, and he was to have lunch with the board of the former students.
And I called over there, and I said, now, Earl, don't get excited, but the house is on fire.
I didn't want him to have a heart attack or something, but...
Actually, what happened, we had this black man named George Washington.
Of course, the kids made up a story about him and said, you'd call over there, and this man's voice would answer.
He'd say, President's House, George Washington speaking.
Well, that was not so.
George would run when the phone rang.
His favorite thing to do was going outside and sweeping the walk so he could watch the students walk by.
He did that endlessly.
But that day, it was Saturday, it burned.
It was a cold, cold and windy day.
And they had painted the house in the fall.
We were just so lucky that it didn't happen at night because most of the windows upstairs were stuck.
And we always felt like we were very lucky in that department.
But George wanted to go to the bank, which was open until noon on Saturday.
And so he called up.
to me and wanted to go.
And I said, OK. Well, unbeknownst to me, he just loaded the fireplace with firewood.
And they came over after the fire, the fire chief did and asked, said, well, hadn't they cleaned the chimney every year?
I said, we've been in it five years and they had never cleaned the chimney.
So the soot caught fire up there.
And there was a former black man that had worked there for the
Okay, I know their name sometime, and other times I can't think of it.
Who was president just before Earl?
David?
Morgan.
Morgan.
I started to say Morgan.
I knew that wasn't right.
Morgan.
He had worked for them, and he said that it caught fire up there once before, and he said he threw a handful of salt onto the burning wood, and it snuffed it out.
I didn't know you could do such a thing.
I didn't either.
Haven't ever tried that.
So you all discovered this at lunchtime?
Well, what happened?
I didn't discover it.
There were two men in a pickup that were driving by, and they said there was just a little flame around where the chimney came out the roof.
And they said, the house is on fire.
Well, Linda and Jane had not even dressed.
It was the days of wearing moo-moos, so they were in their moo-moos.
And Linda ran and looked up in the attic, and she said if she'd have had a fire extinguisher, she could have put it out.
It was such a small...
blame then but anyway the first fire truck that came so the fire chief told us he was so excited about what was burning that he didn't turn the right thing in his fire truck and the

water was not reaching where the flame was so this wind hit it and it's an old frame you know just all right now when did the when did it begin what time of day oh right at noon right at right at noon all right and by what time did you all decide you had uh well see Earl I don't think Earl ever came inside I made three racing trips Earl was getting you know as I said I kept his uniform
for 33 years that we were married before he died, he just left it up to me to keep his uniforms ready to go.
And he was to go to Washington for some military meeting.
And I had been pressing that uniform, polishing the brass, which is over on the dresser.
And anyway, so I grabbed the uniform and raced downstairs with it.
And he had bought me a first stole, so I'd look pretty nice for his inauguration.
I thought, I better get that on, won't get another one.

those two things that i went downstairs and got his military overcoat and his hat whatever you call it put those in the car happened to be at the back in the driveway at the back and so i just threw him in the car then i went back and got oh on the rod about this much i got i could see the two newest suits that i had i thought i've got to have something to wear so
Oh, and we'd change the beds that morning, and in the laundry bag I'd put, because shoes were always a problem for me, and I'd put three pairs of shoes and then dropped it over the stairwell.
But I made three trips.
I went and got things that Ann had brought home from school.
She was home between semesters.
Then a few things out of Bob's room.
And when I started down the stairway, the third trip that I was making, I got choked on the smoke, and the fireman...
told me in no uncertain terms to get outside and not come back in.
So I did.
And I remember a guy that was from here, but he worked for the Daily Texan.
And he wrote a column, of course, and got the paper.
And he said that I had noticed smoke coming through the walls most of the morning, but I hadn't thought anything about it.
I thought, that makes me sound like an idiot.
And I brought it up to him one time much later on.
He said he didn't remember it.
Anyway, Doris Hannigan somehow appeared on the scene and took me over to her house.
What did you all lose that was sentimentally priceless?
Up in the attic I had so many boxes of clippings from the war, like from the Philadelphia War.
